[The article does not tell us what type of remedial action the area is taking. It is likely that, as warning signs have been posted, they will simply let the toxic algae run its course and die off naturally. There are a number of cyanobacteria or blue-green algae that can cause quite serious problems. While this article calls it toxic green algae, it is most likely one of the cyanobacteria or blue-green algae.

Dog owners should be advised to leave the dogs at home, as the blue-green algae can kill canines, horses, cattle, and possibly others. Readers are advised to see the moderator's comments in ProMED-mail posting 20160202.3988561. - Mod.TG

Maps of England can be seen at http://www.picturesofengland.com/images/mapofengland/england-counties.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4489300,33564. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
